<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Hard sell for a new
British cheese - Churnton's confident launch into the mass market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You can almost hear the hoots of derision from across the Channel at the
news that 'an exciting new British cheese' was launched this week. Yet,
after the much-publicised demise of Lymeswold, the imitation blue Brie, the
marketing experts are convinced they have got it right this time.
The Cheese Company, formerly Express Foods and Britain's biggest independent
cheese manufacturer, is oozing confidence. It has spent about Pounds 500,000
developing Churnton - whose name is supposed to conjure up homely images of
traditional cheese-making - and is splashing out Pounds 2.5m on a saturation
campaign of television and magazine advertising, mail shots and in-store
tastings.
Churnton is a hard cheese, made to a secret recipe in the company's creamery
in Malpas, Cheshire. It looks like a cheddar but with an open texture, and
has a fairly strong flavour. Unlike new, specialist farmhouse cheeses,
Churnton is aimed unashamedly at the mass of consumers who buy mild or
medium cheddar for everyday use.
The cheese is being launched first in north-west England, where 18 per cent
of households are 'heavy users' of hard cheeses, and will go national early
next year.
The initial six-week TV campaign began last night with a 30-second
advertisement in the middle of Coronation Street, featuring Victoria Studd,
the popular television presenter, pronouncing: 'After one taste, you'll turn
to Churnton.'
The sales line sprang from the success of trial tastings in Safeway stores
across the country, in which eight out of 10 people said they would buy
Churnton again. It is deliberately packaged to look like an ordinary
cheddar, so 'the trick is getting people to taste it in the first place',
says Maria Dooley, marketing manager.
Price will be important at this end of the market. Churnton will sell at a
slight premium to mild or medium cheddar, but the company has opted for
fixed weight packs starting at 99p for 200g. 'When buying variable weight
packs of cheese, people fish around for the ones that are below Pounds 1,'
says Dooley.
It might seem a gamble to target a new brand at a market which is 85 per
cent dominated by supermarket own-label cheeses, roughly the reverse of
France, where branded regional cheeses abound and the retailing sector is
more fragmented.
Roger Davenport, managing director, explains that 'the relative lack of
branding in the UK is a result of the great success of major supermarket
chains and their drive towards own label'.
But any desire the supermarkets may have for innovation is stymied by
conservative British tastes. Despite the range of hand-made and imported
cheeses on offer, cheddar and other hard cheeses account for more than 75
per cent of sales. That is why Churnton is designed to be familiar, 'while
offering advantages in taste and texture,' he says.
The Cheese Company, which was bought out by its management from Grand
Metropolitan for Pounds 96m only 16 months ago, believes there is room for
growth in the Pounds 1.1bn UK market, of which it expects Churnton to
capture about 2 per cent. British cheese consumption is rising by 1-2 per
cent a year but is still only half that of continental Europe, and a third
of France.
Churnton, according to the launch publicity, is the first British cheese to
be developed for the regular, weekly shopper in more than 50 years.
With weary determination, Davenport fields comparisons with Lymeswold, which
was withdrawn in 1992 a decade after a triumphal start. He says Lymeswold
raised such expectations that the manufacturer, Dairy Crest, could not meet
them and began delivering a product that was not up to initial standards.
'Unlike Churnton, they didn't get much repeat purchasing,' he says. 'Whereas
ours is very much mainstream, Lymeswold was always, however successful,
going to be a niche product.'
Davenport is adamant that the cheese will not be found bland by its target
consumers. There is at least one auspicious sign. When Lymeswold was
launched, Peter Walker, then agriculture minister, was seen on television
feeding chunks of it to his dog Bomba. Gillian Shephard, the present
incumbent, does not have a dog.
</TEXT>
