<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Sex, sense and
sensibilities - A look at the changes in social attitudes behind a rise in
complaints about sexism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Slapped wrists for UK advertisers accompanied the revelation this week that
concern about sexist advertisements appears to be rising. According to the
Advertising Standards Authority's annual report, complaints from the public
about the portrayal of women climbed from 180 in 1992 to 536 last year,
while the number of complaints that were upheld more than doubled from 52 to
111. There is a 'need for greater sensitivity over the use of sex and women
in advertisements', the ASA warned.
But are advertisers really getting worse in their treatment of sex and
women? The indiscriminate use of semi-clad women draped across car bonnets,
or pouting from double-glazing advertisements, for example, seems to be less
common than it once was.
An alternative explanation for the increase in complaints could be the
sharpening of public sensibilities on such issues. According to Caroline
Crawford, ASA head of media relations, a 1980 survey conducted by the
authority showed that women were far more offended by the advertising of
sanitary products than by the sexist advertising that was around at the
time.
A decade later, about one in three women 'felt a degree of animosity about
the demeaning portrayal of women,' says Crawford. The figure for men (who by
this date had also been included in the survey) was about one in five.
'Still the majority weren't that bothered, but those who were bothered were
very bothered. It was an increasingly vocal group,' she says.
The increased use of nudity in recent years may also be a factor. While not
necessarily tasteless, sexist, or irrelevant to the product, it is still
likely to offend a few people.
The current Wonderbra poster campaign is hard to miss and has drawn about 30
complaints to the ASA so far. However, there are no plans to investigate,
says Crawford. The posters are of 'a confident woman of the 1990s who is
very aware of her sexuality and is certainly not a victim,' she says.
Likewise, the recent Haagen-Dazs ads, which showed a couple in various
states of undress enjoying ice cream, was considered by the ASA to be
tastefully photographed and sensitively handled. Even, says Crawford, 'if it
couldn't be said to be completely relevant' to the product, the treatment
probably would not offend the majority of people.
Rita Clifton, director of strategic planning at advertising agency Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi, agrees that nudity in advertising has increased: 'We're not as
uptight about showing naked bodies - they are now an acceptable public
currency for many. What is not acceptable any more - if indeed it ever was -
is portraying a woman as a victim, a stupid partner or somehow not in
control of her own destiny.'
On the whole the ad industry has to toe the line. There are no inflexible
rules - either for printed advertisements, governed by the ASA, or
television commercials, supervised by the Independent Television Commission
 -about which bits of the human body may or may not be shown. Instead,
advertisers have a general duty not to cause offence; how that is
interpreted in each case depends on the context, treatment and innuendo.
For example, a lingerie advertisement from Scandinavian retailer Hennes,
which showed no more cleavage than the Wonderbra advertisement, did fall
foul of the ASA. The strapline on the poster read: 'What the au pair will be
wearing this winter.' Says Crawford: 'Men wrote in and said 'I employ an au
pair and I object to the implication that all an au pair is good for is to
act as a man's plaything'.' What the public does object to, she adds, is
'inept and sexist innuendo' rather than sex itself.
Humour may be the salvation of an advertisement, even if the context for
nudity is questionable. The ITC let a Danepak bacon ad off the hook, in
spite of complaints, because it was judged 'comic rather than voyeuristic'.
The advertisement showed a family of nudists cooking bacon and giving thanks
that the low-fat product was less likely to spit in the pan than other
bacons.
The trade press continues to present problems for the ASA, particularly
those journals with a predominantly male readership. According to Crawford,
there are still ads around with line drawings of buxom women and strap-lines
which say, for example, 'Free sex' and then go on to say 'Now we've got your
attention lads, come and buy our motorbikes.'
The authority got into a scrap last year with a farming publication over an
ad for paper sacks. A 'page three girl', says Crawford, was used,
irrelevantly, to advertise the sacks. Two complaints, one from a man and one
from a woman, were upheld. The publication and the company then started
lobbying farmers and the ASA was accused of being a kill-joy and guilty of
political correctness. 'You try explaining to a farmer the concept of
sexism,' comments Crawford, who has some experience as a member of a farming
family herself.
Rita Clifton at Saatchi questions whether this kind of advertising actually
works - whether it is aimed at men or women. 'Clearly, advertising needs to
grab people's attention. The problem is that if you show a lithe 18-year-old
in a jock strap, quite often that will be the only thing that's recalled by
women,' she says. Unless the product and the figure are properly integrated,
the product may go unnoticed.
The mention of jock straps raises the question of whether men are these days
as likely as women to be victims of sexist advertising. At the very least
they may be the victims of stereotyping, as an article in the current issue
of She magazine points out. Entitled 'Why the man-bashing has to stop', it
lists the current advertising campaigns which portray men as 'ranging from
dim and uncouth, to pushy and insensitive,' and argues that the campaigns
have little appeal to women because 'women do not want to see old sexist
values simply reversed'.
There have been complaints about men and sex in ads - the ASA annual report,
for example, details the case of the recent Britvic orange juice
advertisement showing a man with wings holding a magic wand and wearing a
posing pouch. The strapline read 'Somehow we manage to cram in 12 oranges'.
There were 35 complaints that the ad was offensive but the ASA ruled that
'most readers would appreciate the humour of the image'.
To date, however, Crawford cannot recall a complaint about men in ads having
been upheld - perhaps that awaits yet another shift in public sensitivities.
</TEXT>
