<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Tories on attack over local tax: Curry's claim to undercut
Labour council charges by average Pounds 129 disputed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party yesterday signalled that it will place what it claims
are the high levels of council tax levied by Labour-controlled authorities
at the forefront of its campaign for May's local council elections.
At the party's first campaign news conference for the elections, Mr David
Curry, local government minister, unveiled figures suggesting that nine of
the 10 highest council taxes levied in the next financial year would be in
Labour councils.
He also said that, of the 10 lowest taxes, five would be levied by
Conservative controlled councils, including Westminster, Wandsworth and
Ealing.
But Labour said he had chosen an invalid base of comparison, by assessing
every council on the tax charged to households in band C - which applies to
properties valued between Pounds 52,000 and Pounds 68,000.
Figures from the Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities
showed that 82 per cent of households in Liverpool, which has the most
expensive band C tax, lived in properties below the band C threshold, and
would therefore pay less than the amount quoted by Mr Curry.
In Westminster, with the lowest band C tax, 84 per cent of households are in
properties valued above Pounds 68,000, and would therefore pay more.
Mr Curry said that the government had been officially notified of the
precise levels of council tax to be levied by about 300 of the 419 local
authorities in England and Wales. He said that the figures showed that on
average councils were levying tax increases of 2.7 per cent in the band C
range.
Although the survey is not complete, this is nearly 4 percentage points
below the amount that the government predicted last autumn, when announcing
its grant settlement for 1994-95, and may reflect the determination of
councils to contain taxes in an election year.
Mr Curry said that on the information the government had received Labour
councils would charge Pounds 129 more on average in council tax next year
than Conservative councils. He said that larger council tax bills were often
levied by councils - such as Lambeth, Tower Hamlets and Islington - which
already receive above average grants from central government.
Mr Curry said: 'What we can demonstrate is that we can provide better value
for money and provide better services.'
Mr Jack Straw, shadow local government minister, said that Mr Curry's
figures were 'unconvincing'.
He said: 'You can't trust the Tories to tell the truth on tax, whether it's
on VAT, personal allowances or council tax. They cannot resist twisting the
truth.'
