<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Court to rule on review of councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The High Court will decide tomorrow on applications by three local
authorities for judicial review of the Local Government Commission's
proposals for council re-organisation in north-east England.
A government decision on the area has already been delayed. The commission
said it had failed to consider about 500 letters from local interests that
were sent before the closing date for consultation. As a result an
unprecedented supplementary report on the area will be published.
It seems unlikely, however, that the supplementary report will make
significant changes to the recommendations.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, must wait until the commission's
reports are complete before announcing any decisions on the area. If the
appeal for judicial review is successful, the process could be further
delayed.
Humberside and North Yorkshire county councils, and Ryedale, a district
within North Yorkshire, are all dissatisfied with recommendations which
would see the creation of five all-purpose unitary councils north of the
Humber in place of the current two-tier system.
They say the commission failed to consider properly the possibility of
maintaining the two-tier status quo, and to carry out proper consultations.
The Labour-controlled Association of County Councils said it was 'concerned'
by the commission's 'worrying' mistake. It will instruct its members in
areas not yet reviewed to check that all submissions have been considered by
the commission.
The cross-party Association of District Councils, whose members include
Ryedale, discourages districts from resorting to judicial review, as the
process is costly and delays re-organisation.
Five counties - Avon, Cleveland, Derbyshire, Lancashire and Somerset - have
already been allowed to challenge commission decisions in the High Court.
The judicial reviews for Avon, Somerset and Cleveland will take place on May
23.
In the following two weeks the commission, which is working to a timetable
shortened by the government last September, must announce proposals for
re-organising Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Leicestershire, Oxfordshire,
Cambridgeshire, Suffolk, Staffordshire, Cheshire, Cumbria, Hampshire and
Devon.
Proposals for Kent and Devon may also be announced at the same time, if
severe local disagreements in both areas can be overcome.
</TEXT>
