<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Stress on jobless takes heavy toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unemployed people are 75 per cent more likely to experience a marriage
break-up than those in work, says the most comprehensive survey of
employment and joblessness in Britain.
The four-year study, based on 6,000 individuals in six towns, found that in
spite of experiencing multiple deprivations the unemployed are not becoming
a culturally distinct 'underclass'.
It also found that they are flexible in the work they are prepared to
undertake and have only modest pay expectations.
Almost all unemployed individuals are considerably worse off on benefits
than in work - but married women are more likely to give up work when
husbands become unemployed because of benefits rules.
The survey covered Aberdeen, Coventry, Kirkcaldy, Northampton, Rochdale and
Swindon. It is part of the Social Change and Economic Life Initiative funded
by the Economic and Social Research Council. It is published today in the
book Social Change and the Experience of Unemployment (Oxford University
Press). Average labour costs in manufacturing are lower in the UK than
southern Italy, one of the poorest regions of the European Union, says a
report published by the Low Pay Unit yesterday.
But the research group says the UK's success in creating jobs has been much
less than in countries with higher levels of employment and social
protection.
</TEXT>
<XX>
