<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Labour attacks Major over inflation 'rift'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday seized on remarks about inflation by the prime minister and
the deputy governor of the Bank of England to claim that the two were
'completely at odds'.
Mr John Major said yesterday that inflation was 'under lock and key'. Mr
Rupert Pennant-Rea said it was 'a delusion' to think that Britain had
defeated inflation.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said: 'The prime minister should
clarify his precise inflation target and whether he intends to meet it.'
Mr Pennant-Rea told the Institute of Credit Management national conference:
'It is tempting to feel that Britain has won the war against inflation, so
we can now afford to relax. That is a delusion, and a dangerous one too.'
Underlying inflation, which excludes mortgage payments, was 2.8 per cent in
January, still in the top half of the government's 1 per cent to 4 per cent
target range. The Bank said in its inflation report, published in February,
that the underlying rate would remain in the top half of the range
throughout 1995, and there was an 'asymmetric risk' it would move higher.
Mr Pennant-Rea said: 'We have to keep inflation down in order to sustain
growth. Monetary restraint is not a hair-shirt but it has to be a habit.
After all the unforced errors of the past it will take many years to prove
we have acquired it.'
Mr Major, speaking to businessmen in Portsmouth, was rather more upbeat
about inflation than Mr Pennant-Rea, but his comments about the UK's
economic prospects were in tune with those of the deputy governor.
The prime minister said: 'What I believe we are beginning to get is a
satisfactory platform for sustained recovery with low inflation.'
Mr Pennant-Rea said: 'The economy will soon enter its third year of
recovery, and the pace of that recovery is enough to have started reducing
unemployment. Meanwhile, inflation is low and the government's target is for
it to go lower still.'
Mr Pennant-Rea's speech marked a departure in tone from the customary solemn
phraseology of top Bank officials. In a candid passage about past mistakes
in monetary policy, he said: 'At the Bank of England we are merely part of
the supply lines. As such, we have the ability to mess things up - and our
record shows we have often used it.'
</TEXT>
