<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Open minister suffers brush with the truth: A look at the
aftermath of a verbal slip-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Mr William Waldegrave's judgment the turning point came early yesterday
morning. Emerging, still blinking with sleep, from the front door of his
London home he was met by a barrage of questions from waiting journalists.
'Are you going to resign, Mr Waldegrave?' shouted one. 'Why?' responded the
minister for public services and science. 'For telling the truth,' the
journalist yelled back.
Mr Waldegrave decided he could relax. The row about his public comments on
when governments might or might not consciously mislead parliament was
revealing itself as a media storm in a Westminster teacup.
Speaking a few hours later to the Social Market Foundation Mr Waldegrave was
careful not to blame the media. Instead he quoted Enoch Powell's dictum that
a politician who complains about the media is like a sailor who complains
about the sea: 'We amateur sailors often complain about the sea, but it does
us little good.'
An honest politician in a government which has not won many prizes for
giving straight answers, Mr Waldegrave spent the rest of the day in
television and radio studios explaining what he had originally said to a
Commons committee.
No, he had not suggested that it was proper for ministers to mislead
parliament. Instead, he had pointed to two occasions in the distant past on
which ministers had been economical with the truth about impending
devaluations of the pound.
The row rumbled on. Lord Callaghan protested that he had evaded
parliamentary questions but had never told a lie. Opposition politicians saw
another opportunity to pin the 'sleaze' label on an ever-embattled
government. Mr Waldegrave's enemies on the right wing of the Tory party saw
another opportunity to cast him as an inevitable victim of the next cabinet
reshuffle.
After all, he might well face considerable criticism in the report of the
Scott inquiry into arms-related exports to Iraq. Mr Major could offer him as
a convenient scapegoat.
But thoughtful colleagues believe sacking Mr Waldegrave in the summer would
be a mistake. He may not be the most guileful of politicians but he is an
intelligent one.
His donnish approach to politics is in refreshing contrast to the
instinctively combative approaches of Mr Michael Howard or Mr Kenneth
Clarke. And if he has never courted a constituency among backbench Tory MPs,
he does have the powerful support of Mr Douglas Hurd.
During regular appearances before select committees he conducts a genuine
dialogue with backbenchers, acknowledging the force of criticisms and
enjoying reasoned argument with those of contrary views. His handling of the
government's science policy has won him plaudits. His oversight of the
Citizen's Charter has made the best of a bad job.
This week he made a mistake. His desire to answer MPs' questions led him to
acknowledge a practice that every politician knows to be true but which few
ever admit. In more tranquil times no one would have noticed. But the media
pounces now on every slip - even, it seems, when the minister responsible
for open government tells the truth.
</TEXT>
