<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Waldegrave says he will not resign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Waldegrave yesterday said he had no intention of resigning as the
minister for public services and science over his comments that ministers
had to lie in exceptional circumstances.
But as the prime minister gave his public backing to his cabinet colleague,
Downing Street was forced on to the defensive by a request from Lord
Callaghan for Mr Waldegrave to 'clear my name'.
This was after Mr Waldegrave said the former Labour prime minister had told
untruths during the devaluation crisis of 1967.
Clearly angered by Mr Waldegrave's comments, Lord Callaghan emphasised that
he had chosen his words very carefully, but that he had never lied to the
Commons.
Comments later released on behalf of Mr Waldegrave sought to make it clear
that the minister had not criticised Lord Callaghan's actions.
The comments stressed that the former prime minister was working 'in
extremely difficult circumstances'. Mr Waldegrave 'specifically recognised
Mr Callaghan's difficulties and believed he behaved with propriety. If Lord
Callaghan now feels that Mr Waldegrave has impugned his integrity it is very
clear that is not the case.'
Downing Street described the devaluations under Labour governments in 1949
and 1967 as 'exceptional circumstances in unusual times'.
It was clear, however, that Mr John Major continued to believe ministers
'must be truthful and not mislead the Commons'.
Mr Waldegrave had pointed to two Labour chancellors, Lord Callaghan and Sir
Stafford Cripps, who had been forced to mislead the Commons in order to try
to prevent the devaluation of the pound.
Mr Major said: 'Mr Waldegrave answered an intelligent question frankly about
what had happened under another government a quarter of a century ago.' The
prime minister was asked on the BBC whether lying could be justified in
parliament. He replied: 'Nobody can and nobody does.'
Mr Waldegrave, asked by Jimmy Young on BBC Radio 2 whether he thought he was
going to keep his job, replied: 'That is entirely up to the prime minister.
If ministers are going to be fired for telling the truth, we are going to
get into a very difficult pickle.'
Mr Waldegrave later told his colleagues that he had no intention of
resigning.
Asked earlier if he had blundered by being too honest, he said: 'If the new
line of attack is to say we really don't want ministers to tell the truth on
these matters, we want ministers who give weasel words, I suppose I plead
guilty.'
</TEXT>
