<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Company-car drivers confess to sins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Company-car drivers are nearly twice as likely to break motorway speed
limits than private motorists. They also break speed limits on other main
roads more readily and admit to parking illegally more often.
This unflattering portrait of company-car drivers is set out in the latest
annual survey of the business-car community by polling organisation MORI and
Pragma Consulting. The survey was commissioned by Lex Vehicle Leasing, owned
by Lex Service and finance house Lombard North Central.
MORI's soundings among fleet managers about the differences between men and
women found that 'in general women are thought (by fleet managers) to be
better and safer drivers and that they look after their vehicles better'.
Younger fleet managers were more likely to feel that women made better
drivers.
More pertinent in terms of the costs incurred by companies on repairs and
insurance premiums, when asked 'Who in your organisation has most
accidents?', 43 per cent of the managers said men and 54 per cent saw little
difference. Only 4 per cent said women.
The survey concludes that the percentage of company cars, at 11.3 per cent
of the total, is higher than for several years and that the population has
increased by 50,000 in the past 12 months.
The average age of the cars has fallen from 2.8 years to 2.5 years in the
past 12 months, indicating that companies are increasing the replacement
rate. Mr John Walden, Lex Vehicle Leasing's managing director, sees this as
a sign that business confidence is improving.
He said: 'Companies make investment decisions, like replacing company
vehicles, when they are confident that the business climate is improving.
The survey results . . . clearly indicate a turnaround in business outlook'.
Only 1 per cent of company-car drivers surveyed said their companies were
phasing out company cars.
More than 4,000 stolen cars were offered for sale to dealers in the last
quarter of last year, reflecting a continuing surge in car-related crime and
fraud, according to HPI, the vehicle information tracking agency.
HPI also found last-quarter increases in vehicles written off by insurance
companies being repaired and re-offered for sale, and more cars being
offered for sale while still subject to hire-purchase agreements.
The agency makes about 3.5m vehicle-background checks a year for auction
houses and the motor trade.
Mr Brian Bailey, HPI's chairman, said part of the rise was likely to be
seasonal and related to financial pressures in the approach to Christmas.
But there was also a 'worrying underlying trend' driving the statistics
upwards.
1994 Lex Report on Motoring - The Company View. Lex Vehicle Leasing, Globe
House, Parkway, Globe Park, Marlow, Buckinghamshire SL7 1LY Pounds 150.
