<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Rethink on crime payouts rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is determined to press ahead with changes to the criminal
injuries compensation scheme, in spite of claims that the reforms will
unjustly reduce payments to victims, Kevin Brown writes.
A senior official said there was no question of a rethink on the proposed
changes, which would replace individual assessments with a fixed tariff.
Labour said yesterday that the tariff would reduce payments to sexually
abused children, families of murder victims and injured police.
The reforms have been criticised in the Lords, where peers said they could
be unconstitutional and open to judicial review.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, is understood to have taken legal
advice which supports the government view that the changes can be
implemented in April as planned.
Downing Street insisted that the scheme would remain the most generous in
Europe.
Officials said that some payments would rise. Compensation for aggravated
rape will rise from an average of Pounds 9,500 to Pounds 10,000, and
payments for facial scarring will rise from an average of Pounds 6,000 to
Pounds 7,500.
However, there was unrest among Conservative backbenchers about the
government's admission that the reforms will cut the cost of the scheme from
some Pounds 500m to about Pounds 250m a year.
It was also disclosed in the Lords last night that Sir Patrick Mayhew,
Northern Ireland secretary, is considering extending the changes - which
apply to England, Wales and Scotland - to Ulster.
</TEXT>
