<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Wider financial regulatory net urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of savings products such as Tessas, which were seen as alternatives
to investment products, should be included in the retail financial services
regulatory regime, a Standard Life executive told MPs yesterday.
Mr Jim Stretton, the life insurance company's deputy managing director, told
the cross-party Commons treasury committee inquiry into financial regulation
that the rules should cover all products which seemed to be in competition
with each other. These included some of the building societies' savings
vehicles, which customers saw as quite similar to unit trusts.
Mr Stretton again signalled that Standard Life was likely to join the
Personal Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect private
investors, in spite of the company's preference for a single-tier statutory
regulator. He resigned from the PIA board because most of its members would
not come from the financial services industry so, he said, it would not be
real self-regulation.
He expressed some sympathy for proposals by Mr George Greener, chairman of
Allied Dunbar and Eagle Star, for a single regulator in which an executive
committee of people working in financial services was supervised by a board
of public interest directors.
He made it clear, however, that he did not believe there was enough common
ground among the PIA's opponents to prevent the watchdog becoming
operational in the summer.
</TEXT>
