<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / NUM in ballot on new structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Union of Mineworkers yesterday started balloting its Yorkshire
members over merger plans which, if defeated, would spell the end for the
union's structure.
A close vote could even bring into question Mr Arthur Scargill's presidency,
although those campaigning against the executive admitted yesterday that
such an outcome was unlikely.
The merger vote has been brought to a head because the NUM, which had
245,000 members in 1982, has about 8,000 members, nearly 6,000 of whom work
in the Yorkshire area.
This has led to rationalisation plans including the takeover of the
Yorkshire area's Pounds 5.8m assets to help ease the union's financial
crisis.
A ballot is necessary to achieve the merger because of the NUM's federal
structure.
Mr John Walsh, agent and assistant general secretary of the Yorkshire area,
dismissed in January but still in post pending an appeal, has said that he
has been victimised for campaigning against the transfer, saying it will be
detrimental to the union.
Mr Walsh believes the union's national headquarters in Sheffield is
virtually penniless.
He said: 'I think it will be almost down to the reserve fund by now and that
can only be used to back up the pension schemes. It has fixed assets
probably of about Pounds 2m but it can't sell the building because nobody
wants it.'
The NUM executive has said in a letter to Yorkshire members that a merger
will avoid an increase in contributions and save the area and the national
union Pounds 200,000 in administrative costs alone.
</TEXT>
