<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Merseyside told to rethink EU bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission in Brussels has rejected government proposals for
spending Pounds 690m of EU money to revive Merseyside's flagging regional
economy.
The commission argues that the plans, submitted late last year and calling
for about half the money to go into training, concentrate too much on
solutions which have already failed and show policies for obtaining EU funds
rather than regenerating the area.
Brussels officials have told civil servants and Merseyside political leaders
to rethink their strategy to give a bigger role to the private sector, which
had complained about lack of involvement, and to concentrate on five 'growth
drivers' - human resources, cultural industries, large industries,
knowledge-based business, and small and medium-sized companies.
The five-year 'Objective 1' status money offers funds to areas which has a
gross domestic product per person under 75 per cent of the EU average.
Rejection of the plans was welcomed by Mr Alan Arthur, chairman of coatings
business King and Fowler and organiser of a 500-company local private-sector
pressure group backed by the Confederation of British Industry.
He said: 'Business people need to be able to use this opportunity. So far it
has looked like only benefiting every advisory body and consultant who was
ever born.'
</TEXT>
