<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Japanese clear way for Jeep
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan is expected to clear the way today for the US vehicle manufacturer
Chrysler to boost substantially its exports to Japan of Jeep Cherokee sports
utility vehicles, in what appears to be part of a campaign to ease trade
tensions.
Chrysler said yesterday that it had been told at short notice that a
vice-minister in the Transport Ministry would present the company with a
'type certificate' at a meeting in Detroit today.
The certificate allows Chrysler's distributor in Japan to carry out
road-worthiness inspections of Cherokees rather than having to submit each
vehicle for certification by the Transport Ministry.
US car manufacturers have long complained that the ministry inspections are
an important non-tariff trade barrier.
Chrysler, which was told some time ago that it was likely to get a type
certificate, plans to boost its Japanese sales of Cherokees from 4,000 a
year to 10,000. However, a spokeswoman said yesterday that Japan still had a
long way to go to open up its vehicle market.
</TEXT>
