<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Suzuki to export cars from India - Geneva
Motor Show
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Suzuki, the Japanese carmaker, is to begin exporting cars to west Europe
from India. Later this year it will launch in Europe its Alto minicar
produced by Maruti Udyog, its Indian production base.
The car was launched last summer in India, where it is sold as the Maruti
Zen. The Alto is the first model Suzuki has developed at an overseas
production base for introduction in overseas markets.
Maruti Udyog is India's largest car manufacturer and was the first
large-scale Japanese-Indian joint venture. It is 50/50 owned by Suzuki and
the Indian government. Maruti is expanding its production capacity from
130,000 vehicles a year at present to 200,000 by the end of the year in
order to expand sales in both the domestic and export markets.
This spring it will produce its one millionth vehicle since it began
production in 1983 under India's 'people's car plan'. It controls 70 per
cent of the Indian car market.
Suzuki's move to begin supplying the European market from India comes at a
time when it is has run into serious problems with its production plant in
Spain, where it assembles small four-wheel-drive sports/utility vehicles,
the Vitara and the SJ series.
Santana Motor, its 82 per cent owned Spanish subsidiary has recently applied
for protection from creditors under pressure of mounting losses, and Suzuki
has threatened to close the plant unless it receives state aid. Suzuki also
has an assembly plant in Hungary, from which it will export cars to west
Europe next month.
</TEXT>
