<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Gatt seeks to expand its HQ in Geneva
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
High-level negotiations are taking place between the Swiss government and
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade on practical and financial
arrangements for Gatt's change of status next year to a fully-fledged World
Trade Organisation. Office accommodation, meeting facilities, parking and
the issue of diplomatic status for senior officials top Gatt's list of
concerns.
Trade officials warned that if satisfactory arrangements were not made the
WTO could look for another home. 'Negotiations are going fairly well. The
Swiss recognise the need to keep the WTO in town,' one official said
yesterday.
Competition for international agencies, including financial inducements, has
intensified in recent years, partly for reasons of prestige but also because
of the boost to the local economy. International organisations and diplomats
account for 9 per cent of employment in Geneva and bring in SFr1.5bn (Pounds
702m) a year to the Swiss city.
Mr Arthur Dunkel, former Gatt director-general and now chairman of a new
private foundation to promote Geneva as an international centre, is said to
be playing a behind-the-scenes role in the negotiations.
Office accommodation is one key factor. The size of the WTO's staff is
certain to be much larger than the 450 now employed by Gatt. Gatt wants to
expand into the whole of its present lakeside building, part of which is now
occupied by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
Though the UNHCR is due to move into purpose-built offices this September,
these were planned when the agency was much smaller and there is now not
enough room for all 800 headquarters employees.
Berne has, however, already approved SFr34m to build a new WTO council room.
The present one can no longer accommodate delegates from all Gatt's 116
member nations plus observers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
