</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / World Trade News: US seeks 'fairer' export control - A look
at proposals to lift cold war-based curbs on trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
From its inception, the administration of President Bill Clinton has made
business its business - in particular high -technology business - and
competitiveness has been given the highest priority.
Despite budget stringency, millions of dollars are flowing into
public-private technology partnerships, Mr Clinton's people fought their
labour and liberal allies to clinch the North American Free Trade Agreement
and the Uruguay Round and officials roam the world hawking contracts for US
companies.
There has, however, been one big disappointment for business. With the end
of the cold war, exporters had high hopes that Mr Clinton would lighten one
of their heaviest burdens: export controls on dual-use and high-technology
products.
Last month Mr Clinton announced proposals for a much-delayed Export
Administration Act, the law governing export controls, and called for
far-reaching licensing liberalisation. The aim has shifted from denying
products to communist nations to controlling the spread of weapons of mass
destruction.
Mr Clinton's proposal calls for strengthening the role of the US Commerce
Department in the approval process. It seeks a rigorous evaluation of
controls, including their economic impact, before they are imposed; the
lifting of old controls that are clearly ineffectual; and simplification of
the licensing process, which would result in an answer to the most
controversial applications within 90 days.
It would introduce the concept of 'unfair impact', allowing industry to
petition for removal of controls based on whether similar products might be
available from other suppliers abroad, on competitive disadvantage or
ineffectiveness of the control.
Business reaction to these proposals have ranged from unimpressed to
hostile. Many computer companies say that no unilateral controls are
necessary because computers have been found to do nothing to aid weapons
proliferation.
Mr Howard Lewis, vice-president of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said that without a total overhaul licensing could cost the
US Dollars 30bn (Pounds 20.5bn) a year in exports by the mid-1990s.
But the president's plan 'would create a system of unilateral controls
loosely co-ordinated with other countries. It would not establish clear
authority and accountability for running the system. And it would not do
enough to tell US companies clearly what, and to whom, not to export', he
said.
Mr Peter McCloskey, president of the Electronic Industries Association, said
the proposed EAA was 'woefully inadequate'.
'Rapidly changing product life cycles necessitate an export control system
that can react quickly and focus only on those technologies that are
critical for the development of weapons of mass destruction,' he said.
Industry has taken its case to Congress where favoured legislation,
sponsored by Delaware Senator William Roth and Minnesota Congressman James
Oberstar, is to be written by a House banking committee today.
This bill would do away with all national security controls imposed
unilaterally on the grounds that critical technologies can best be curbed by
co-operation between supplier countries. It would strengthen international
export controls by extending preferential treatment to countries which agree
to abide by common standards of licensing and enforcement.
It wants business input in multilateral negotiations to establish stricter
controls on a smaller list of strategic commodities.
'Excessively long control lists only spur resistance from allies and
ultimately hinder the effectiveness of control regimes,' said the Coalition
for Fundamental Reform of the Export Control System.
While business is pushing for a multilateral solution, the US and its allies
in the Co-ordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls are meeting
in Paris this week to wind up the organisation's affairs. CoCom is to go out
of business on March 31, and with no great common enemy to unite them, the
allies are far from agreeing a successor organisation.
Russia is to join the new group, which will focus on controls of dual-use
goods and conventional arms to outlaw regimes such as Iran, Iraq, and North
Korea. In the absence of agreement, the US has been expected to propose
continuation of the current control lists.
Meanwhile, Congress must either hope that one day an effective multilateral
regime will be in place, muddle along with sporadic unilateral controls
which disadvantage US industry or lift all export licensing requirements
except for those products most egregiously dangerous.
</TEXT>
<XX>
