<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Judge rules out claim by Mirror
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A judge has ruled that one of the late Robert Maxwell's companies had no
right to a claim against the New York Daily News, the tabloid newspaper
owned by Maxwell when he died, Reuter reports from New York.
The ruling, made on Tuesday and released yesterday, settled the final
dispute in the newspaper's bankruptcy that came shortly after Maxwell died
in November 1991.
Mirror Group Newspapers claimed the paper stole Dollars 92m (Pounds 63m)
from the group, saying Maxwell and his son, Kevin, took the money to run the
Daily News.
The US bankruptcy judge denied the Mirror claim, saying the Maxwells lied to
the tabloid's directors and their actions hurt the Daily News as well as the
Mirror Group.
The judge said the father and son engaged in an 'elaborate ruse', concealing
the source of money to the newspaper and planned to strip the tabloid of
even more money at a time when its ability to publish was in jeopardy.
</TEXT>
