<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / IADB members raise - and lower - the stakes: A look at a
capital-boosting deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US and its Latin American partners have agreed to reduce their stake in
the Inter-American Development Bank as part of an accord to boost the bank's
capital by Dollars 40bn (Pounds 27bn).
The agreement, which will reduce the US shareholding in the bank to around
30 per cent from 34.6 per cent, also envisages the bank lifting its current
bar on lending to the private sector.
The capital increase, if details are finalised as expected at the bank's
annual meeting in Guadalajara, Mexico, next month, would allow the bank's
non-regional members - particularly Japan and Germany - to expand their
small stakes in the institution.
Japan, which currently holds only 1.08 per cent of the bank's capital, has
been pressing for an expansion in its stake to reflect its financial support
for US initiatives in Latin America. The agreement is also expected to
provide Japan with an executive director on the board, which will be thus
expanded to 13 members.
As part of the accord, the borrowing members of the bank from Latin America
and the Caribbean will reduce their combined stake from 53.8 per cent to a
fraction over 50 per cent.
The Dollars 40bn increase should allow the bank to continue with a lending
programme of Dollars 7bn-Dollars 8bn a year for an indefinite period.
Only 2.5 per cent of the increase will be paid in by shareholders, the rest
being callable capital against which the bank will be able borrow in capital
markets. The increase in the stake of the non-regional shareholders will
reduce considerably the budget implications for the US, which is currently
Dollars 847m in arrears in its commitments to international institutions.
The bank's lending to the private sector will be limited to infrastructure
projects, with a ceiling probably of 5 per cent - Dollars 350m to Dollars
400m a year. The bank will only lend where the private sector is also
providing finance, and to a maximum 25 per cent of total lending.
Under the accord, the bank will double the proportion of its lending going
to so-called social sectors, such as primary health and education which are
now considered the central issue for the region's development. Some 50 per
cent of transactions (40 per cent by value of lending) will be directed to
these areas. The bank will also direct lending for the first time to improve
the quality of government - for instance, enhancing the region's judicial
systems.
Mr Enrique Iglesias, the bank's president, said the capital replenishment
accord was 'more than a capital increase. It's a redefinition of bank policy
to better respond to Latin America's problems.' However, there was still
much to do before the increase was finally agreed.
This includes completing discussions about the bank's soft-loan window, the
Fund for Special Operations, and resolving differences over whether another
seat on the board is required for the bank's Latin American members as
Chile, especially, is seeking.
However, a US Treasury official was optimistic that the issues could be
resolved by the Guadalajara meeting and remarked on the 'positive manner' in
which the discussions had been held.
</TEXT>
<XX>
