<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Police open fire on 'homeland' demonstrators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MMABATHO, BOPHUTHATSWANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Riot police fired at demonstrators in the South African black 'homeland' of
Bophuthatswana for the second day running yesterday as a civil service
strike paralysed the government of increasingly embattled homeland leader
President Lucas Mangope. At least 32 people were wounded, witnesses said.
The homeland government said a police officer was killed.
President Mangope, who yesterday closed down the broadcasting service and
sacked all of its staff, rejected a request from the Independent Electoral
Commission to allow campaigning and polling for the April elections to take
place in the homeland. Bophuthatswana said earlier this week it would not
participate in these elections.
As teargas drifted toward the government offices from the nearby University
of Bophuthatswana, Finance Minister Ephraim Keikalame admitted candidly to
journalists: 'It is not possible to have an effective functioning government
under these circumstances.'
Almost the whole of the public service appeared to be on strike, including
essential services like hospitals, but telephones and electricity continued
to function. The capital's main hospital complex was deserted by staff, with
some patients lying unattended.
Outside the university, pol-ice armoured vehicles roared up and down
throughout the day, firing teargas cannisters and rubber bullets at students
barricading the entrance gate.
The rioting provoked a threat of direct South African intervention, with the
Transitional Executive Council, the multi-party body overseeing government
in the run-up to elections, saying it would give President Mangope a week
'to change his attitude' after which steps would be taken to force
reincorporation.
</TEXT>
