<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / MEPs reject car pollution curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Parliament yesterday rejected proposals to tighten
anti-pollution regulations against car manufacturers from 1996. MEPs threw
out the proposals after strong opposition from the European Commission and
the auto industry which argued it threatened jobs and investment. The vote
opens the way for passage of existing proposals gradually to limit car
emissions through legislation due to come into force in 1996. The car
industry has been working toward a set goal of lower emissions, but became
alarmed after the parliament's environment committee introduced a raft of
amendments for tougher standards and a faster timetable. The amendments also
demanded a 50 per cent increase in air quality standards, as well as new tax
incentives for clean cars and a carbon tax to limit fuel consumption. The
second reading vote at the Strasbourg parliament was eagerly awaited because
it provided a test of the Maastricht treaty's new clauses on co-decision. If
the amendment had secured the 260 votes necessary for passage, it would have
gone back to the Council of Ministers which would have been forced to broker
a compromise or face a showdown with a newly assertive parliament.
