<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Greece and Macedonia close to deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE, JUDY DEMPSEY, LIONEL BARBER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS, LONDON, STRASBOURG, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A possible breakthrough in the dispute between Greece and Macedonia emerged
last night before both sides meet under UN auspices in Geneva today. If
resolved, it could help shore up a fragile stability in the southern
Balkans.
Mr Cyrus Vance, a former US secretary of state and UN mediator in former
Yugoslavia, will discuss the draft accord with Greek foreign minister
Carolos Papoulias and Mr Stevo Crvenkovski, his Macedonian counterpart.
Under the proposed agreement, Macedonia would immediately alter its flag
which carries a starburst symbol linked with the ancient Greek kings of
Macedon. In return, Greece would drop its veto on Macedonian membership of
the Conference for Security and Co-operation in Europe and participation in
the European Union's aid programme for eastern Europe.
Greek officials have indicated the embargo would be lifted as soon as
Macedonia put another symbol on its flag and gave assurances the
constitutional issue would be addressed.
The possibility of movement follows this week's decision by the EU and the
Commission to soft-pedal on earlier threats of legal action over Greece's
trade embargo, and to acknowledge there is a 'political' element to the
Macedonia dispute. In Strasbourg, Mr Papoulias said the EU's stance had
given Athens room for manoeuvre.
Today's talks coincide with cabinet meetings in Britain and Canada to decide
how many troops, pending support from other countries, they will send to
Bosnia to shore up the ceasefire. Lieutenant General Jean Marcotte, the UN's
military spokesman in Zagreb, Croatia, said yesterday that any delay in
sending troops 'would place the peace process in a critical situation'.
Other countries, including Bangladesh, Pakistan, and particularly Turkey
which has 1,000 troops on standby, have offered reinforcements. But Mr
Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, has ruled against sending
troops from neighbouring countries.
The US, which has refused to send ground forces to Bosnia until a full peace
agreement is signed, was yesterday understood to be considering boosting its
force in Macedonia from 300 to 700. This would allow a 400-strong Nordic
force stationed in Macedonia to be sent to Bosnia.
France will offer more troops on a 'roll-over' basis, sending in forces
earlier to overlap with those on the ground. The Nordic countries said they
were prepared to re-deploy troops from Croatia.
General John Shalikashvili, chairman of the US joint chiefs of staff, said
yesterday that some 50,000 western troops, half of them American, would be
needed to oversee any Bosnian peace agreement, Reuter reports from
Washington. He was challenging earlier reports that a smaller force of
20,000-30,000 troops, perhaps a third of them American, could monitor any
final peace deal.
Political notebook, Page 8
</TEXT>
