FT  10 MAR 94 / Norway unflustered by collapse of talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Norway yesterday appeared unflustered by the hiatus in its fraught
negotiations on terms for entry to the European Union as the government
presented the wrangles within the EU on the talks as evidence that it was
driving a good deal for Oslo, writes Hugh Carnegy in Stockholm.
Mr Jan Henry Olsen, the Norwegian fisheries minister - given a virtual veto
on the country's entry terms by Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland - said
he would recommend acceptance of a proposed deal blocked only by Spain when
the talks stalled in Brussels. 'If Spain accepts the proposed solution on
fish already accepted by the 11 other EU members and Norway, I will say yes
to membership and recommend others to do the same,' said Mr Olsen formerly a
staunch opponent of Norwegian entry to the union.
In Stockholm, Mr Carl Bildt, Swedish prime minister, said he was not
concerned by the delay in Brussels. 'This is not a breakdown in
negotiations, but a one week delay. There is no reason to believe Sweden's
entry will be delayed,' he said.
