<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Catalonia sees war of words as dangerous fantasy: A look at
the growing row over the Catalan language law which has been referred to
Spain's highest court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Scoop, the British writer Evelyn Waugh's seminal satire on journalistic
jaunts, a celebrated war correspondent sent to cover a revolution in a
Balkans capital oversleeps in his train carriage, wakes up in the wrong
city, blithely rattles off dispatches about flaming churches and dead
children, and succeeds in creating financial panic, famine and a revolution
on his hotel doorstep.
Waugh's fable resurfaced two weeks ago in an editorial on the Catalan
language question in the Barcelona newspaper La Vanguardia. Mr Jordi Pujol,
president of Catalonia's autonomous government, the Generalitat, since 1980,
has since seized the story to explain in subsequent press conferences that
the supposed row is a fantasy which could turn dangerous.
At issue is a Catalan language law, unanimously passed by Catalonia's
parliament 11 years ago in one of Mr Pujol's earliest legislative
initiatives, that has been referred by the Supreme Court in Madrid to the
Constitutional Court, an even higher Madrid-based judicial body whose 12
members are the watchdogs of civic rights and duties.
The Constitutional Court has to decide whether the language law infringes
the rights of Spanish speakers in Catalonia by forcing them to learn
Catalan, a language that the post-Franco constitution asserts is co-official
with Spanish in the area. It is expected to spend months pondering over its
ruling. In Mr Pujol's view there is no issue and no row - only interested
parties who seek to rock Catalonia's calm.
The Scoop-like correspondent creating the storm is a well-known extreme
right-winger in Barcelona and a lawyer, Mr Esteban Gomez Rovira, aided and
abetted by the conservative Madrid newspaper ABC.
Mr Gomez Rovira has been fighting legal battles to curb the growing use of
Catalan in the area's schools ever since the language law was enacted. In
1985 and 1987 he survived bomb attacks from Catalan extremists. His latest
assault, now before the Constitutional Court, follows what he terms 'a turn
of the screw by the Generalitat'. The twist by Mr Pujol's government, which
has so far gained the backing of the judiciary for its educational
initiatives, has been its insistence on Catalan-only schooling for children
up to the age of seven under a new policy called 'linguistic immersion'.
Mr Gomez Rovira sees the development as one step further in the creation of
a monolingual culture that will destroy 'the unity of Spain'.
ABC has given the lawyer a platform for his views ('it has made all the
difference', he says).
The newspaper claims that Mr Pujol is seeking to stamp out Spanish just as
Francoism sought to eradicate the language of Catalonia.
Surveys conducted by the Generalitat, and a succession of views in Barcelona
from a cross-section of native Catalans and of immigrants to the area,
suggest a very different picture to the one painted by ABC. The vast
majority are functionally bilingual; they do not question the Generalitat's
weighting towards Catalan and they are not 'unlearning' their Spanish.
Unlike other minority languages that have become nationalist emblems,
Catalan is a romance language that is easy to learn and, more importantly,
it is very much a living language that carries social prestige.
Immigrants from southern Spain, who swelled Barcelona dormitory towns such
as Santa Coloma from 12,000 in the 1950s to 140,000 today, wanted to learn
the language of the foreman on the building site and in the workshop.
Mr Pujol's education department claims that over the past five years the
percentage of Catalonia's 6m inhabitants that does not understand Catalan
has been reduced from 9.4 per cent to 6.2 per cent; nearly 94 per cent
understand Catalan, 68 per cent can speak and read it and 40 per cent can
write it.
The department's officials say that far from discriminating against
immigrants, the 'linguistic immersion' policy wants to ensure that children
from Spanish-speaking homes will have an equal opportunity in a schooling
system where more than half the subjects are taught in Catalan.
To date, less than 500 parents have backed Mr Gomez Rovira's campaign to
demand Spanish-language schooling with Catalan as an optional subject.
Mr Pujol believes that the cornerstone of continued calm and consensus in
Catalonia is the maintenance of the present impulse towards cementing a
bilingual society.
He fears that the Constitutional Court might, like Mr Gomez Rovira and the
Scoop journalist, wake up at the wrong station, and create an artificial
conflict by upholding a dual schooling system that would prove dangerously
divisive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
