<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / A tale of paper cod and accelerated cohesion fish: The Greek
handling of the talks unravelled the EU's Byzantine solution to the fishing
row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A dispute over the conduct of the talks, rather than the content of the
negotiations, appears to have stood in the way of the European Union
clinching entry terms with Norway late on Tuesday night, when ministerial
negotiations in Brussels on EU enlargement broke up in disarray
Mr Javier Solana, the Spanish foreign minister, walked out of the
negotiations for some two hours, irritated by the way the Greek presidency
of the EU presented Spain with what he evidently saw as a 'take it or leave
it' offer on access to Norwegian fish, without allowing time for the Spanish
to examine the details.
Spanish officials at the meeting nevertheless confirmed that they were
prepared to give serious consideration to the content of the offer.
The main obstacle to concluding terms with Norway is Spanish insistence that
it get back the 7,000 tonnes of cod its fishing fleet used to catch in
Norwegian waters before it was barred in 1981.
Madrid equally wants the cod Norway ceded to the EU as part of this year's
European Economic Area (EEA) free trade zone treaty 'consolidated' as part
of a permanent quota. This amounts to 7,250 tonnes this year, rising to
11,000 tonnes in 1997, with the so-called 'cohesion' or poor countries,
Spain and Portugal, getting 45 per cent each, and Greece and Ireland
splitting the rest.
But for over a year Oslo has unflinchingly refused to give up a single extra
fish. 'I will stand tall and firm and say No,' Mr Jan Henry Olsen, Norway's
fisheries minister, said on Tuesday, as Spain reiterated its threat to veto
Norwegian entry unless he budged.
The European Commission's alchemists, however, were busy working up a
seemingly impossible formula to save the face of both Madrid and Oslo. Its
main elements are:
To bring forward the 11,000 tonnes quota for 1997 to this year (these are
known as 'accelerated cohesion fish').
Under the EEA, the Union also gets 2.9 per cent of the total Norwegian
waters cod quota, or about 40,000 tonnes this year. But the cod stock is
rising because of careful Norwegian fisheries management, promising a higher
tonnage for the EU in coming years. Brussels wants to satisfy Spain's
demands by giving it these additional tonnes (known as 'paper fish', because
at the moment they are only there on paper).
Anticipating that Spain will not be satisfied, the Commission has also
looked at 'other people's fish'. Brussels suggests the Union buys a portion
of Russia's cod quota in Norwegian waters, allocate it to Spain, and pass
the bill through Oslo's contribution to the EU budget.
Norwegian officials, with whom this formula had to be worked out, were
obviously familiar with the details of this package; Spanish officials,
equally obviously, were not. When Mr Theodoros Pangalos, the Greek European
affairs minister chairing the EU Council of Ministers, presented Spain with
what it regarded as a fait accompli, Mr Solana took it as an affront and
left for his embassy.
Spanish officials say they need time to study the implications, but concede
that the Commission formula could turn dross, or at least cod, into gold.
</TEXT>
<XX>
