<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Barclays considers default provisions to limit profit swings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Barclays, the largest UK bank, is working on plans to even out cyclical
swings in its profits by making a small provision for default each time it
lends money. It hopes this will prevent large rises in loan provisions
during recessions.
Mr Martin Taylor, Barclays' new chief executive, is backing the initiative
although it was discussed before he took up his post full-time in January.
Barclays announces its 1993 profits today, after a Pounds 242m loss in 1992.
Banks suffered from an unprecedented swing in their profits in the five
years from 1987 because they boosted earnings by increasing loans rapidly in
the late 1980s. They were then hit by a wave of bad debt provisions in the
recession.
Banks carry general provisions against losses they expect from loans which
appear to be sound, but Barclays wants to make this more exact. It would
book a small loss against each loan, set according to the chance of it not
being repaid. The bank is trying to analyse the risks over full economic
cycles of particular types of lending, such as small corporate loans or
those to particular industries. Mr Taylor is thought to be keen to implement
the new approach next year.
Barclays' directors believe that by making loans carry a small provision
based on risk, they could discourage branch managers both from lending too
much during economic booms and refusing loans during recession.
However, the initiative could be hard to implement because of the difficulty
of assessing risk accurately. The move could also be opposed by bank
auditors, who might regard it as an attempt to smooth profits by mis-stating
earnings.
The bank could also increase its tax liability by making general provisions.
Specific provisions against loans clearly in danger of default are tax
deductible, but general provisions against expected loss are not.
Barclays signalled a move towards evening out volatility in profits when it
increased its general provisions by Pounds 118m in the first half of 1993.
It holds general provisions worth about 0.6 per cent of its loans and
advances.
Mr Taylor is thought to be keen to implement the idea in full. If Barclays
cannot gain approval from auditors, it might bring in the change internally
in separate management accounts.
Mr Taylor is thought to be keen to implement the idea in full. If Barclays
cannot gain approval from auditors, it might bring in the change internally
in separate management accounts.
Mr Taylor was chosen as chief executive last autumn after the bank faced
strong criticism for its performance.
</TEXT>
