<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Ban on use of BT lines for TV to continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has ruled out any early lifting of the ban on British
Telecommunications using its network to carry television broadcasts, despite
BT claims that Britain risks losing out to international competitors in the
information revolution.
Mr Patrick McLoughlin, the telecommunications minister, has written to the
Cable Television Association, which represents the cable companies building
combined phone and television networks in urban areas, to reaffirm the
government's commitment to maintaining the restrictions on BT.
He said the government would stick to the terms of the 1991
telecommunications white paper, which imposed a ban on BT carrying
entertainment services in order to foster greater competition in
telecommunications.
The most significant part of the ban is the block on BT offering additional
TV over its network. It appears not to extend to video on demand.
The government's determination to curb BT emerged as Sir Iain Vallance, BT's
chairman, warned MPs that Britain would lose its leading telecoms position
in Europe unless BT went ahead soon with the construction of a national
fibre network.
Sir Iain told the House of Commons trade and industry committee, which is
studying options for such a network, that uncertainty over the future of the
enter-tainment ban was hampering BT in its investment planning.
'BT has a leading position in the UK in fibre technology,' Sir Iain said.
But its lead was 'partial and tenuous' and without a lifting of the ban it
was 'difficult' to see how BT could justify the Pounds 15bn investment
necessary to extend fibre to most of the country over the next decade.
The fibre would replace copper wires in the local networks, giving
flexibility and capacity for a range of new interactive services.
Sir Iain likened the possible consequences of failing to upgrade local
networks to the decline of the UK's manufacturing industry in the 1980s,
against competition from the Far East.
According to a senior Whitehall official ministers believe BT is engaged in
an elaborate bluff to secure an early lifting of the ban.
Under the 1991 white paper, BT is banned from carrying entertainment
services over its network until 2001, although Oftel, telecoms regulator,
can recommend lifting the ban from 1998.
BT is about to start a pilot project at Kesgrave, Suffolk, taking fibre
technology into 70 homes, providing services such as video on demand down
upgraded lines. Sir Iain agreed that a lifting of the ban in 1998 would not
significantly hamper BT.
Mercury to spend Pounds 200m, Page 7
</TEXT>
