<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / International Company News: Paramount and QVC show bid
battle scars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Paramount Communications, the film and publishing group being acquired by
Viacom after a Dollars 10bn takeover battle, yesterday reported a
third-quarter net loss of Dollars 36.6m, due largely to disappointing
audience figures for some recent film and television shows.
The loss was in line with a forecast loss of Dollars 35m to Dollars 40m
which Paramount made last month in the final stages of the takeover battle
between Viacom and QVC Network, the television home shopping channel.
QVC yesterday reported fourth-quarter net income of Dollars 2.8m, or 6 cents
a share, down from Dollars 18.9m, or 40 cents, in the same period of last
year, after taking Dollars 34.8m of pre-tax costs (an Dollars 18.8m net
loss) for its unsuccessful Paramount offer.
However, QVC's operating income in the fourth quarter was 34 per cent
higher, at Dollars 53.2m, compared with Dollars 39.5m, on revenues up 9 per
cent at Dollars 372.5m, compared with Dollars 341.8m. Fourth-quarter net
income also included a Dollars 1.1m extraordinary charge from the
accelerated write-off of debt placement fees.
Mr Barry Diller, chairman, said the results confirmed QVC's core business
was strong and 'though obviously somewhat distracted while pursuing
Paramount, we have not been deterred from our strategy to put in place an
aggressive plan for growth in both our basic business and the emerging world
of inter-activity'.
For the full year, QVC reported net income of Dollars 59.3m, or Dollars 1.18
a share, compared with Dollars 55.1m, or Dollars 1.24, on sales 14.2 per
cent higher at Dollars 1.22bn.
Paramount's third-quarter net loss, which worked through at 31 cents a
share, compared with a net loss of Dollars 66.8m, or 56 cents, in the same
period of last year, when it took a Dollars 66.9m one-time charge for an
accounting change. Revenues were Dollars 1.01bn, up from Dollars 943.7m.
For the first nine months, earnings totalled Dollars 180.6m, or Dollars
1.50, against Dollars 149.9m, or Dollars 1.26, the previous year.
