<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / International Company News: McDonnell Information joins
market worth Pounds 260m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
McDonnell Information Systems is coming to the market through a placing and
public offering at 260p a share, valuing the Hemel Hempstead-based computing
services company at Pounds 260m.
Some 73.1 shares are being issued, of which 42.5m are new shares with the
balance being sold by existing shareholders. Some 35 per cent of the offer,
which closes on March 17, is available to the public. Dealings commence on
March 24.
The flotation will raise Pounds 110m of new equity and Pounds 80m for
existing shareholders. The net proceeds, Pounds 107.4m, will be used to
repay debt and redeem preference shares.
MDIS management bought the company from McDonnell Douglas of the US for
Pounds 121m last year. Mr Jeremy Causley, chief executive, said he would not
be selling his shares. After the flotation management will hold 7.6 per cent
of the equity.
On a post-flotation pro forma basis, the company had pre-tax profits of
Pounds 21.3m in the year to December 1993. Out of earnings per share, it
would have paid a notional net dividend of 6.25p a share.
The placing and offer, one of the largest flotations this year and the
biggest in the information technology field, has been fully underwritten by
Baring Brothers, which is to sponsor the issue.
COMMENT
MDIS is a mature company with revenues of almost Pounds 150m and a record of
management competence. Operating profits as a percentage of turnover have
risen from 10 per cent to 15 per cent in the past three years in spite of
the recession. The company specialises in areas such as central and local
government, the emergency services and the health sector, which will show
sound, if not outstanding, growth. As a public company, it could reasonably
hope for more success in bidding for larger contracts. The offer price
suggests a p/e of 18.2 that is fractionally higher than the sectoral
average. Notional gross dividend yield at the offer price is 3 per cent. The
shares seem fairly priced and should prove a core holding for computing
services aficionados.
</TEXT>
