<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Brent Intl pay-out cut after fall to Pounds
7.14m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Brent International, the troubled speciality chemicals group whose chief
executive resigned in August, is cutting its dividend after pre-tax profits
slumped from Pounds 11.5m to Pounds 7.14m in 1993.
Profits for the year to December 31 were struck after Pounds 289,000 of
compensation to former chief executive Mr Steve Cuthbert, who had a two and
a half year contract at a salary of Pounds 135,000.
Mr Keith Hutchings, the former finance director who has been acting chief
executive since his departure, said the scale of compensation reflected the
fact that Mr Cuthbert was over 50.
Exceptionals of Pounds 3.91m included Pounds 580,000 of costs relating to
acquisitions which were aborted early in the year when the scale of the
group's problems became clear.
Earnings per share dropped from 10p to just 3.2p. There was a reduced final
of 2.4p (5.8p) leaving a total of 4p (7.4p).
The profit figure includes gains of Pounds 6.76m on the disposal of
businesses.
Sales from continuing operations rose 5 per cent to Pounds 114m. Excluding
exceptionals, operating profits in the continuing businesses fell from
Pounds 9.3m to Pounds 6m.
The company said there had been some improvement in the UK and US but not in
continental Europe which accounts for 43 per cent of sales.
However, Lord Lane of Horsell, chairman, said, 'the lower cost base from
which we now operate should enable us to make further progress in 1994.'
Mr Hutchings was yesterday confirmed as chief executive, with Mr Bill
Jessup, former finance director of Beauford, the struggling engineering
group, replacing him as finance director. Lord Lane will retire next year
and be succeeded as chairman by Mr Alec Daly, who joined the board a year
ago.
The shares fell 15 1/2 p to 105p.
</TEXT>
