<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Reorganisation costs hit MR-Data profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR-Data Management, the data transcription and document image processing
group, reported lower interim pre-tax profits reflecting one-off
reorganisation costs, lower net interest income and development costs in its
Memex software division.
In the six months to December 31 profits fell by 34 per cent to Pounds 2.66m
(Pounds 4.02m) on turnover up 5 per cent to Pounds 19.6m (Pounds 18.6m).
Earnings per share declined to 3.21p (4.89p). However, the interim dividend
is being raised by 20 per cent to 2.076p (1.73p) reflecting the group's
strong balance sheet and cash position.
Mr John Redmond, chairman, said: 'During the past months we have reorganised
our business resulting in significant one-off costs which have been absorbed
in the first half. Additionally profits have been affected by the on-going
development costs at Memex.'
Operating profits slipped to Pounds 2.83m (Pounds 3.02m). The 1992 figure
was boosted, following accounting rule changes, by the writing back of
Pounds 651,000 of acquisition provisions. The 1993 figure was reduced by
reorganisation costs of Pounds 382,000.
</TEXT>
