<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Fisons plans cuts as profit tumbles: Drugs side to shed
1,000 jobs - 30% of scientific instruments division to be sold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fisons, the UK pharmaceuticals group which dismissed its chief executive in
December, yesterday said it had identified further scope for cost cutting as
it unveiled a slump in trading profit from Pounds 117m to Pounds 37.4m.
Mr Patrick Egan, chairman, said its cost reduction programme would cut
overheads by an annualised Pounds 38m over two years, compared with the
previous forecast of Pounds 35m.
The programme, which will involve the loss of 1,000 jobs in the
pharmaceuticals division, follows a review by accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand
which cost Pounds 4m.
Mr Egan also revealed the group planned to sell about 30 per cent of its
scientific instruments division, which incurred losses of Pounds 39.6m,
including a restructuring charge of Pounds 20.7m.
In December, Fisons sacked its chief executive, Mr Cedric Scroggs, who had
been directly responsible for the scientific instruments division, and
warned the group would only break even for 1993. The company hopes to
announce a replacement for Mr Scroggs in the next few months. 'We are
absolutely determined to get it right and I am not going to be rushed,' said
Mr Egan.
The figures were also hit by the decision to end the practice of boosting
pharmaceutical sales just before the year-end by offering discounts. This
reduced profits in 1993 by Pounds 32m though Mr Mike Redmond,
pharmaceuticals managing director, stressed: 'We will be selling in January
and February what we would have sold in December.'
After Pounds 40m of exceptional items, trading profit from pharmaceuticals
fell Pounds 29.2m to Pounds 42.2m, with sales from continuing businesses up
7 per cent to Pounds 446m, while profits from laboratory supplies rose from
Pounds 25.9m to Pounds 27.6m.
At the pre-tax line, profits fell from Pounds 124m to just Pounds 1m after
losses on business to be discontinued of Pounds 32.9m. There was a loss per
share of 3.3p, compared with earnings of 13.9p.
Spending on research and development rose from Pounds 64.5m to Pounds 72.5m.
Thanks to disposals, an operating cash outflow of Pounds 69m after tax and
dividends became a cash inflow of Pounds 152m and gearing fell from 67 per
cent to 40 per cent. In line with December's announcement, the final
dividend is cut from 5.4p to 1.0p.
