<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Counties attacked over spending on publicity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers have fuelled the row over the English local government review by
attacking Essex and Surrey county councils for spending too much on
literature publicising their case.
Both counties responded that their spending was necessary to meet
requirements set by the Local Government Commission. They said district
councils, which Department of the Environment ministers excluded from
criticism, had spent far more.
Most district councils favour creating small, all-purpose unitary
authorities while counties prefer either the existing two-tier system of
counties and districts or the creation of large unitary authorities. All
councils are expected to make submissions to the commission by the end of
May.
Essex said it 'absolutely refuted' the charge. It said the county had still
not decided on a new structure to recommend to the commission, and had so
far spent only Pounds 10,000 on a consultation leaflet, of which 25,000
copies had been printed.
Surrey estimated its expenditure - incurred producing two leaflets and
commissioning a Harris poll of residents - at Pounds 20,000.
Mr Michael Jennings, deputy chief executive, said this had been incurred
under guidance from the commission. He estimated that the 11 Surrey district
councils had spent 'at least Pounds 100,000' on the review.
Each of them paid Pounds 7,500 to CSL, the managed services division of
accountants Touche Ross, to prepare financial estimates for their
submission, which calls for five or six unitary councils.
</TEXT>
