<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Government split over control of education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A split between the prime minister's office and the Department of Education
opened yesterday over future local government control of education.
Mr Graham Bright, parliamentary private secretary to Mr John Major, appeared
to tell his local county council in a letter that local government
re-organisation in England would mean the abolition of local education
authorities.
He said: 'I very much hope that Bedfordshire County Council will recognise
that the introduction of grant-maintained status for schools is permanent
and that its own imminent demise signals the end for local education
authorities.'
But the education department said that it had no plans to abolish local
education authorities 'in the lifetime of this parliament'. Local government
re-organisation is due to take place in 1995 and 1996, before the next
general election is due.
Education ministers have, however, strongly encouraged schools to opt out of
local authority control, and instead take their funding directly from
Whitehall.
Labour seized on Mr Bright's comments as an admission of a Tory 'hidden
agenda'. Education is a county responsibility in non-metropolitan England,
and counties are due to be split into smaller all-purpose authorities under
the government's guidance to the Local Government Commission. It had been
assumed that the new unitary councils would inherit responsibility for
education, the largest single item of local government spending.
County education officers oppose re-organisation, saying that it would
weaken services.
Mr Bright attacked 'the re-creation of the old local authority empire over
schools', saying this would favour 'the most hidebound vested interests in
education'.
Bedfordshire, which has no overall political control, said that 13 of the
county's schools had opted out, while 277 remained in county control. It
added that Mr Bright appeared to have prejudged the outcome of the review,
which could still, under government guidelines, recommend that the two-tier
system continue.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said the comments were 'a
mixture of admission of the government's hidden agenda, and a sign of
desperation that the grant-maintained schools are not catching on in
anything like the way the government intended'.
She added that the practical problems of abolishing local education
authorities would be too great, as the government would not be able to run
schools in the country.
</TEXT>
