<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Labour attacks cuts in criminal injury awards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was forced on to the defensive yesterday by Labour attacks on
plans to speed up the criminal injuries compensation scheme.
Mr John Major defended the government's plans to replace individual
assesments with a tariff scheme during irritable question time exchanges.
The prime minister said the changes, which will take effect in April, would
make the system more efficient and speed up payments to claimants. But it
later emerged that the changes would reduce the annual bill for compensation
payments from about Pounds 500m a year to Pounds 250m by the end of the
decade.
The government expects 46 per cent of claimants to be worse off under the
new system, which will replace individual assessment with fixed payments.
The proposals have been criticised in both houses of parliament, and there
is growing unrest among Conservative backbenchers about the impact on the
victims of crime.
Mr John Smith, Labour leader, sought to exploit Tory unease by claiming that
compensation for police officers seriously injured in criminal attacks would
fall from Pounds 121,000 to Pounds 7,500. He said that a young woman with
two children who saw her husband murdered at her own front door had received
Pounds 137,000 under the existing scheme, but would have received only
Pounds 17,000 after April.
'Why should she lose Pounds 120,000 under a government cost-cutting
exercise?' he asked. 'Is it not bad enough that crime has doubled under this
government without making the victims pay for it?'
</TEXT>
