<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Canal paths used for fibre-optic grid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Competition for long-distance telecommunications traffic was stepped up
yesterday by the launch of a company using Britain's canal tow-paths to
build a fibre-optic network.
Fibreway says it is the first company engaged solely in the wholesaling of
capacity to other operators. It will offer no services directly to
end-users, but will sell capacity to the growing array of entrants to the UK
market.
Construction of a link between Edinburgh and Glasgow is under way, with
others planned in the Midlands. With more than 2,000 miles of canal
available, the potential exists to create a network linking most of the UK's
biggest cities. The three existing long-distance networks are owned by
companies which also provide telecoms services to consumers. They are
British Telecommunications, Mercury, and Energis, which will launch a
service next month.
Fibreway's largest shareholder is GPT, the telecoms equipment joint venture
between GEC and Siemens, the German group. It is acting in partnership with
British Waterways. Mr Gerry Boothroyd, Fibreway's director, said that
initial investment would be in the 'tens of millions', with network
construction determined by demand.
Cable companies building local networks in urban areas are keen to see a
diversity of long-distance operators.
Mr Eugene Connell, head of UK operations for Nynex, the US group making
significant UK cable investments, expressed 'serious interest' in the new
operator as a means of linking Nynex's franchises in different parts of the
country.
The idea of using canal tow-paths for a telecoms network has been in the air
for several years, but appeared to founder two years ago when Sprint, the US
long-distance carrier, dropped plans to build its own UK network.
The railways are already used for telecoms. Part of Mercury's long-distance
network runs alongside the tracks, and British Rail's own telecoms
subsidiary is preparing to offer a service to outside operators.
</TEXT>
