<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Spate of TV mergers attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission's chief executive last night attacked
the recent spate of takeovers in ITV and suggested that they were driven
more by ambition than commercial considerations.
Mr David Glencross said in a hard-hitting speech to the Royal Television
Society that the advantages of size were not as clear-cut as often claimed.
He was speaking as MAI's bid for Anglia Television went unconditional and
after Carlton Communications's takeover of Central and Granada's successful
hostile bid for London Weekend Television.
Some time and expense would be saved by simplifying decision-taking in ITV
but, he said, takeovers were driven by three factors. 'In order of priority
they are ambition, ambition and ambition.' He added that already nearly
Pounds 50m had been spent in servicing the deals.
Even the newly enlarged ITV companies were small by international standards
and it was a misconception to think size by itself would create a thriving
programme export business.
Mr Glencross said: 'There is nothing to stop a consortium of the ITV
companies, and the BBC too, if it wishes, getting together to produce for
the export market without any change in the ownership rules.'
The government decision to allow larger ITV companies to be taken over by
each other had 'added to, rather than resolved the uncertainty about the
future of ITV'. Smaller companies could be left dangerously exposed.
Mr Glencross criticised the 1990 Broadcasting Act for making the ITV
companies the most taxed television companies in the world. Last year Pounds
360m, a quarter of ITV's advertising and sponsorship revenue, went to the
Treasury, almost as much as the total revenue of Channel 4.
He added: 'So in effect the cost of an entire national television channel is
being handed to the Treasury in addition to the normal corporation tax paid
by the Channel 3 companies.'
The ITC chief executive also said that:
Newspaper stakes in ITV should be able to rise from 20 per cent to 30 per
cent but that limit should be applied by stages to satellite groups such as
British Sky Broadcasting, half-owned by Mr Rupert Murdoch's News
Corporation.
A new Channel 5 could start within two years without inhibiting the launch
of digital services.
</TEXT>
