<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / From sop to soap-opera success: The S4C channel's rise to
Oscar contender
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In its early days so few people watched S4C, the Welsh fourth channel, the
joke was that it would have been been cheaper to give Welsh speakers free
video recorders.
More than a decade later all that has changed. The television channel that
was seen as a political sop to the Welsh nationalists has not only found an
audience and helped to stimulate a television and film production industry,
but even has a seat at the Oscars ceremony in Los Angeles later this month.
The Welsh-language film Hedd Wyn, the story of a poet from Trawsfynydd and
his death in the trenches during the first world war, is one of five
nominations for the foreign film Oscar.
S4C commissioned and paid for the Pounds 700,000 film, which has already won
a Royal Television Society award for best UK drama.
'I'm keeping my fingers crossed that I may go out with an Oscar,' says Mr
Geraint Stanley Jones, who retires at the end of next month after five years
running the channel.
'What it means is that finally there's a recognition that small could be
quite good actually and that a funny language may not be that restrictive,'
says the S4C chief executive who was formerly the BBC's first managing
director of regional programmes.
Recently S4C has migrated from Wales to BBC 2 with its Welsh language soap
opera Pobol Y Cwm - People of the Valleys. The popular drama, complete with
English sub-titles, has been getting afternoon audiences of about 600,000.
With the original S4C viewing attracting audiences of about 250,000, 1m
viewers for Pobol Y Cwm might be possible in future.
The channel broadcasts 32 hours a week in Welsh, although a growing
percentage of Welsh-language programmes carry English sub-titles. The rest
of the time S4C reschedules popular Channel 4 programmes such as Brookside
and The Big Breakfast.
Placing more emphasis on drama and English sub-titles has resulted in
increased ratings. In November 1988 the top 10 Welsh-language programmes
averaged 74,700 viewers each. By November 1992 this figure had risen to
125,600 and by last November to 202,700.
S4C is now funded by a 3.2 per cent share of non-satellite advertising
revenue - which includes income from the breakfast franchise and Channel 4 -
paid in the form of a block grant from the Treasury via the Department of
National Heritage. Last year this accounted for Pounds 55.7m. The channel is
also free to sell its own advertising and is expected to raise Pounds 6m
this year.
It also expects Pounds 10m in co-production money - S4C has made programmes
with broadcasters as diverse as ZDF of Germany, ABC of Australia and
Fujisanki of Japan, with a particular emphasis on animation.
The animated tales of Shakespeare sold to 50 countries and the station is
working on a multi-million pound animation of the Old Testament with
Christmas Films of Moscow.
As Mr Stanley Jones hands over to the new chief executive Mr Huw Jones, a
leading Welsh independent producer, it seems a very reasonable legacy for a
channel born after Mr Gwynfor Evans, president of Plaid Cymru, the Welsh
nationalist party, threatened to go on hunger strike if one was not created.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Channel Four Television.
</CO>
<XX>
