<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Lib Dems target urban Tory seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats yesterday outlined plans to target urban Conservative
seats in an attempt to establish the party as the main metropolitan
alternative to Labour in the May local government elections.
Launching a paper on urban policy Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat
leader, said Britain's rundown cities could be regenerated through
decentralisation and wider council powers over taxation and planning.
The paper, Reclaiming the City, aims to build on the Liberal Democrat's
successes in last year's county council elections, when the party made
widespread gains at the expense of the Tories. It attacks the government for
imposing undemocratic quangos on local government and 'failing either to
arrest the underlying processes of urban decay or to ameliorate the
effects'.
Mr Ashdown said the paper was intended to challenge the public view of the
Liberal Democrats as a rural party of the south-west of England, Scotland
and Wales.
'Up and down the country we are moving away from being a party exclusively
winning seats in rural areas and one which is becoming an inner-city
alternative to the Labour party,' he said.
The paper is based on the Liberal Democrats' long-standing commitment to
decentralise local government under a new tier of regional assemblies for
Scotland, Wales and the English regions.
It calls for lower business rates; local agencies to mobilise savings and
channel national and European funds into development projects; tax relief
for municipal development bonds; and workforce agreements to ensure that
local people benefit directly from jobs created by redevelopment projects.
It also urges the use of planning law to direct businesses and homes back to
inner-city areas, combined with a development tax to discourage development
on greenfield sites.
The paper also calls for a substantial increase in light rail and other
public transport systems.
</TEXT>
