<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Economic indicator's rise ends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recent rise in the Central Statistical Office's longer leading index has
ended, new data showed yesterday. The index is designed to detect turning
points in the economy about a year in advance.
The index, whose components include the yield curve, building starts, the
financial balances of industrial and commercial companies and business
optimism, is now flat. This is mainly due to a large downward revision to
December's housebuilding figures.
However, the shorter leading index - intended to highlight changes in
activity about five months ahead using share prices, car registrations and
the Gallup index of consumer confidence - continued its 15-month rise.
The coincident indicator, which tracks the business cycle, has risen
steadily from its trough in the second quarter of 1992. All its components -
including GDP at factor cost, industrial production, retail sales and M0
money supply - have contributed this year.
</TEXT>
