<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Malaysia still cool after Prior visit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Senior Malaysian officials have warned that it may take some time for
Britain to improve relations. This is in spite of attempts by leading
British business figures to persuade Kuala Lumpur to lift an order banning
UK companies from participating in new government contracts.
Dr Mahathir Mohamad, Malaysia's prime minister, yesterday had a lengthy
meeting with Lord Prior, chairman of GEC and a former British cabinet
minister.
Although British diplomats in Kuala Lumpur stressed that Lord Prior's
secretive two-day visit to Malaysia was private, a senior official in London
said the mission 'had the blessing of Downing Street'.
Lord Prior was believed to be on his way back to London last night and is
expected to report to Mr John Major today on his meeting with Dr Mahathir.
Sir Charles Powell, a director of Trafalgar House and former foreign affairs
adviser to Mr Major and Baroness Thatcher, has also been in Malaysia.
GEC is among the British companies hardest hit by the Malaysian ban.
Together with Trafalgar House and Balfour Beatty, it is part of an
Anglo-Japanese consortium which had been hoping to carry out a large part of
the work on a new Pounds 3bn international airport outside Kuala Lumpur. GEC
has also sold defence equipment to Malaysia under the controversial 1988
memorandum of understanding between the two countries.
Malaysian officials privately admit that Dr Mahathir is unlikely to take any
quick decision to rescind his government's order against British companies.
It is felt that Dr Mahathir wants a more outspoken condemnation from Downing
Street of reports in the British media - in particular a report in The
Sunday Times - alleging that he and other members of the Malaysian
government had been involved in seeking under-the-table payments from a
British company.
</TEXT>
