<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Ministers' lies to MPs defended by Waldegrave
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister, yesterday rekindled the
controversy over ministerial accountability raised by the arms-for-Iraq
affair when he appeared to defend lying to parliament.
Mr Waldegrave told the Commons Treasury and civil service committee that
ministers could be justified in 'very, very exceptional cases in saying
something that was untrue'. He added: 'Everyone accepts that.'
Mr Waldegrave said: 'Much of government activity is more like playing poker
than chess. You don't lay all your cards on the table.'
Mr Waldegrave's admission followed questioning over evidence given by Sir
Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary, to the Scott inquiry, which is
investigating the sale of arms to Iraq.
Sir Robin told the inquiry that giving incomplete answers to parliament was
frequently necessary. He added, however, that half-answers should not
mislead MPs other than in 'the most exceptional circumstances . . . like the
devaluation case'.
Mr Waldegrave repeated this formulation to the committee, and added that
ministers often could not tell the House all that they knew, 'especially in
relation to diplomatic matters'. He pointed out that parliament had appeared
to accept that it was right for the government not to reveal everything that
it was doing in order to bring peace to Northern Ireland.
Committee members expressed surprise at Mr Waldegrave's robust defence of
the practice. Mr Giles Radice, the committee's chairman, said that it was 'a
remarkable statement for a minister'.
Mr Quentin Davies, Tory MP for Stamford and Spalding, said the Commons had
on occasion accepted that ministers had to lie in the national interest. He
added, however, that it was the usual practice for a minister to offer his
resignation afterwards.
Mr Michael Meacher, shadow Citizen's Charter minister, called on the prime
minister to repudiate Mr Waldegrave's 'accommodation with dishonesty'.
He said: 'Trust and credibility are at the heart of democracy. If this
dangerous and highly damaging doctrine were once accepted, confidence in
ministers, already at the lowest ebb since the war, would completely
collapse.'
Mr Waldegrave told Channel 4 news that he was 'astonished' by the storm
raised by his remarks, which were directed solely at the 'exceptional' case
of an impending devaluation.
</TEXT>
