<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Dartford bridge likely to pay for itself by 2001
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Dartford bridge, the first project to be completed under the
government's initiative for private funding of transport links, is expected
to pay for itself by the year 2001, seven years ahead of schedule.
More than 37m vehicles used the crossing last year, generating income from
tolls of Pounds 41m, the Department of Transport said yesterday. The bridge,
which carries the M25 motorway across the Thames east of London, was
completed a little over two years ago for Pounds 86m.
Mr Robert Key, transport minister, said the success of the Dartford
crossing, officially called the Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, showed the value
of the government's private-finance initiative.
However, other attempts to bring private finance into infrastructure
projects have been blamed for delays in getting work under way.
The Dartford bridge was built and financed by a consortium consisting of
Trafalgar House, the construction company, merchant bank Kleinwort Benson,
Bank of America and the Prudential insurance company. They were awarded a
concession to collect tolls for up to 20 years.
Once the consortium breaks even on the bridge, ownership will transfer to
the government, which may then levy tolls for one year. If it wants to
continue tolls for longer it must seek parliamentary approval, although the
transport department hopes to introduce tolls on the entire motorway network
from 1998.
The British Road Federation said the bridge had ended congestion on the
river crossing but it owed much of its success to a lack of alternative
bridges or tunnels east of London.
The Automobile Association said motorists would be surprised the tolls had
been set at a level allowing such prompt repayment of the bridge's debts. It
called for the tolls to be dropped when the bridge reverted to public
ownership.
</TEXT>
