<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Mercedes in Indian venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mercedes-Benz is to start assembling E-Class executive cars and
manufacturing vehicle engines in India in a new joint venture with its
long-standing partner, Tata Engineering and Locomotive (Telco) of Bombay.
The partners will invest DM250m (Pounds 97.2m) in equipping a factory in
Poona with capacity for 20,000 cars and 50,000 petrol and diesel engines a
year.
Car assembly will start this year, while engine output is scheduled to begin
in 1995, Daimler-Benz, the Mercedes parent, said yesterday.
Mercedes will hold a 51 per cent stake in a new operating company,
Mercedes-Benz India, which will further tighten ties with Telco, in which
Daimler has a 10 per cent stake.
The two groups have co-operated since 1954, when Telco was awarded its first
licences to manufacture Mercedes commercial vehicles under licence.
