<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 94 / Clinton puts faith in top lawyer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday reached into the upper echelons of the
Washington establishment for assistance over the Whitewater affair by
appointing Mr Lloyd Cutler, the celebrated Democratic lawyer, as his new
White House legal counsel.
Mr Cutler, 76, who served in the same capacity in the troubled last year of
the Carter administration, said yesterday he would concentrate on
'procedures and actions necessary to maintain public confidence in the
integrity and openness of the presidency'.
The White House has said for several days it was looking for 'a Lloyd Cutler
type figure' of unquestioned stature to replace Mr Bernard Nussbaum, whose
resignation was announced last weekend.
Mr Cutler said he was supposed to be 'counsel to the president in office and
to the office of the presidency' but would not handle Mr Clinton's personal
affairs dating from before he took office.
News of the appointment did not deter Republicans insisting hearings be held
into allegations the White House has sought to obstruct investigations into
the Whitewater affair, which involves Mr and Mrs Clinton's land and
financial dealings in Arkansas in the 1980s.
Congressman Newt Gingrich of Georgia said yesterday the legislature 'has an
independent obligation to investigate and to inform both itself and the
country'. Republicans have already threatened to hold up the nomination of
Ms Ricki Tigert to run the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation if
Democrats refuse to agree to hearings.
Mr Gingrich also dismissed objections from Mr Robert Fiske, the independent
counsel probing Whitewater, who said hearings on Capitol Hill 'would pose a
severe risk' to the integrity of his inquiries.
Mr Fiske is mindful of the Iran-Contra precedent, where grants of immunity
from prosecution given by Congress as a pre-condition for testimony
ultimately resulted in the conviction on criminal charges of Oliver North
being overturned.
But Mr Jim Leach from Iowa, senior Republican on the House banking
committee, said there was no reason why anybody testifying over Whitewater
should be granted immunity. His committee already has plans to question
Treasury officials later this month.
The Democratic leadership in Congress, according to Mr Leach, is now on the
horns of a dilemma, not wanting to appear to obstruct the probe but also not
wanting to embarrass the president, orjeopardise his legislative programme.
Mr Tom Foley, the Speaker of the House, has warned against the legal
complications that might follow hearings, but has not come out flatly
against them. Yesterday, Senator John Breaux, the Louisiana Democrat,
speaking of the 'partisan setting' of Congress, said: 'We don't need
political hearings, we need legal hearings.'
Mr Clinton opened up one possible new avenue of inquiry on Monday when he
said he had been told last October that federal regulators wanted a criminal
investigation of Madison Guaranty, the Arkansas savings and loan institution
at the heart of the affair.
He insisted this information had been routinely passed on to him and was the
limit of his knowledge of contacts between the White House and other
departments. Yesterday Mr Clinton stoutly defended himself. 'I still haven't
been accused of doing anything wrong, because I have not done anything wrong
and I am not going to do anything wrong.'
</TEXT>
