The two parties in France's ruling coalition, the Gaullist RPR and the
centre-right UDF, yesterday negotiated a common policy platform for this
June's European elections, ending the threat of rival electoral lists, which
would have split the government of Mr Edouard Balladur. The coalition, which
is expected to be approved by the parties' leaders later today, is likely to
win up to 40 per cent of the vote, according to opinion polls, making it by
far the largest force. The opposition Socialists are expected to take less
